        "text": "Reception, Recovery, Reinvention of the Ancient World in Current Popular Culture The Present of Antiquity, 265â€‘294\n\nAntiquity has been a great source of inspiration for videogames since their advent. Together with the growing impact that videogames have on contemporary society, their use of historical or mythology-related themes and elements has recently begun to attract a certain amount of academic attention. 1 While from a scholarly perspective the reception of classical antiquity is bound to be the central focus, it ought to be remembered that videogames are, first and foremost, entertainment: the ludic aspect and game mechanics are thus a primary concern, and historical or mythological accuracy usually has to take a backseat. To mention just one example, in strategy games that allow human players to compete against each other by choosing a different faction (i. e. Romans vs. Egyptians), concessions to gameplay balance have to be made in order to give each faction the same chance of winning, which inevitably detracts from historical accuracy. Nevertheless, it is worth exploring how classical antiquity exerts an influence on video game content, from isolated hints of mythology to a deeper use of an historical setting. The integration of generic elements in a different, typically fantasy, context in videogames is a widespread phenomenon, since it is often an attractive option for their creators due to the convenience of integrating some already existing content. 2 By and large, this kind of process focuses on historical or mythological elements that are most immediately recognizable to the general public; that is, those elements that, for one reason or another, already form part of popular culture to a certain extent, with all\n\nAntiquity in Videogames. Genres and Approaches"
